Developer uses reinforcement learning in Codex to build a living creature s=
im
6,050 Likes
Someone used
OpenAI Codex
(an AI that writes code for you) to build a tiny self-righting robot from s=
cratch. The robot falls over, then gets back up on its own. That's harder t=
han it sounds.
Here's how it works. The robot was first trained inside a
physics simulation called MuJoCo
, where an AI learned by trial and error, thousands of times, how to stand =
back up. This "learn by trying" approach is called reinforcement learning. =
Once the AI got good at it in simulation, that trained brain was exported a=
nd flashed onto a real physical robot.
The robot body was 3D printed and runs on 2 servo motors
The AI brain runs on an
M5Atom
, a tiny microcontroller smaller than a matchbox
The trained policy (the AI's decision logic) was converted into a plain C h=
eader file and compiled directly onto the chip
What this opens up: you can train smart behavior in simulation for free, th=
en drop it onto cheap hardware. No cloud, no GPU at runtime.
