<div style=3D"margin-top:0;">
<p>Someone used <b>OpenAI Codex</b> (an AI that writes code for you) to bui=
ld a tiny self-righting robot from scratch. The robot falls over, then gets=
 back up on its own. That's harder than it sounds.</p><p>Here's how it work=
s. The robot was first trained inside a <b>physics simulation called MuJoCo=
</b>, where an AI learned by trial and error, thousands of times, how to st=
and back up. This "learn by trying" approach is called reinforcement learni=
ng. Once the AI got good at it in simulation, that trained brain was export=
ed and flashed onto a real physical robot.</p><ul><li>The robot body was 3D=
 printed and runs on 2 servo motors</li><li>The AI brain runs on an <b>M5At=
om</b>, a tiny microcontroller smaller than a matchbox</li><li>The trained =
policy (the AI's decision logic) was converted into a plain C header file a=
nd compiled directly onto the chip</li></ul><p>What this opens up: you can =
train smart behavior in simulation for free, then drop it onto cheap hardwa=
re. No cloud, no GPU at runtime.</p>
</div>
